            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Versioning is a hard thing.\r\n\r\nHowever, all dependencies of Flask are pallets projects, which makes things easier to maintain than NodeJS. When people using Flask, should we expect that they are also using Werkzeug, Jinja2, itsdangerous and click directly? I don't think so. Even if they are using them directly, it won't break things too much/often.\r\n\r\nThe situation of @jeffwidman is really bad. But it has nothing to do with Flask's versions. That global environment will fail sooner or later if they are going to upgrade something.\r\n\r\nMy suggestion is that we keep a newer version of the dependencies, but not necessary to be the latest. "
        },
